            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> Judging from the linked readme this isn't the case? It uses vim.g.rustaceanvim\n\nSorry, should've included a link to where the configs are merged: https://github.com/mrcjkb/rustaceanvim/blob/4c5fc771694ab09ec618ea2baabaf34420d86edb/lua/rustaceanvim/lsp/init.lua#L165\n\n> probably also doesn't play nice with type checking when you have unknown keys in vim.lsp.Config?\n\nThe plugin providing the option can extend the type\n\n```lua\n--- @class vim.lsp.Config\n--- @field bar string\n\nlocal foo = {} --- @type vim.lsp.Config\nfoo.bar -- typed\n```\n\n> Why would one want to do that anyway? It obfuscates what belongs to what\n\nI think it makes sense from a user's POV that you would configure all options related to the LSP in one spot, rather than split between `vim.g.rustaceanvim.server` and `cmp.lsp.config`. From a plugin author POV, you don't need to re-invent the `lsp.config` API if you need to support more than one LSP. With keys like `blink_cmp`, I feel like it's clear that the option belongs specifically to that plugin.\n\n```lua\nvim.g.rusteaceanvim = { server = { ra_multiplex = { enable = true } } }\nrequire('blink.cmp').lsp.config('rust-analyzer', { frecency = false })\n\n-- becomes\n\nvim.lsp.config('rust-analyzer', {\n  ra_multiplex = { enable = true }\n  blink_cmp = { frecency = false }\n})\n```",
