            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> From the rustaceanvim docs (:h rustaceanvim.Opts):\n\nThis to me isn't entirely clear if it is primarily about merging `vim.lsp.Config` settings, or also the rustaceanvim specific properties.\n\n> Sorry, should've included a link to where the configs are merged: https://github.com/mrcjkb/rustaceanvim/blob/4c5fc771694ab09ec618ea2baabaf34420d86edb/lua/rustaceanvim/lsp/init.lua#L165\n\nLooking at the implementation it almost seems a bit like working by accident to me.\n\nEspecially with the `default_settings`. It is redundant as it is the same as `settings`. Not sure why one would set `default_settings` via `vim.lsp.config` if you can set `settings` directly instead.\n\nMaybe @mrcjkb could clarify.\n\n\n> From a plugin author POV, you don't need to re-invent the lsp.config API if you need to support more than one LSP. With keys like blink_cmp, I feel like it's clear that the option belongs specifically to that plugin.\n\nIsn't `blink_cmp` also supporting non-LSP features. So you have part of the config done via vim.lsp.config, and part via some custom blink.cmp mechanism? Wouldn't that be more confusing for users?\n\n---\n\n\n> An advantage of setting stuff directly on the Client object is that, similar to buffers/windows/tabpages, it is very useful to have the state get garbage-collected when the object goes out of scope.\n\n`vim.lsp.config` isn't bound to the `Client` instance lifecycle.\n\nI could see the appeal for runtime state. And I could also see additional value if it were about a plugin using `LspAttach`/`client.config` - to account for users setting instance specific configuration values by using `vim.lsp.start` (client scoped config instead of server scoped).\n\nBut so far none if this was mentioned. My distaste for mixing plugin/core settings into the same bag probably comes a bit from DAP and how vscode extensions freely intermix client and server settings, making it very confusing for users moving to other clients which then don't support the vscode-extension specific settings.\n\nIf we support something like this, I think we should at least have a dedicated `plugins` property to be explicit.\n",
