            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "A bit of history from my side:\n\nrustaceanvim's configuration was designed before `vim.lsp.config` was a thing.\nIt uses a `vim.g.rustaceanvim` config table, which has 3 fields[^1]:\n\n- `tools`: Plugin configuration.\n- `dap`: Configuration of the nvim-dap integration.\n- `server`: LSP client configuration template.\n\n[^1]: The field names come from rust-tools.nvim, of which rustaceanvim was a fork.\n\nThe type of `server` is not `@type vim.lsp.ClientConfig`, but `@type rustaceanvim.lsp.ClientOpts`, which rustaceanvim uses as _a template_ to generate a `@type vim.lsp.ClientConfig`.\n\nAt some point, quite a few users started asking for the ability to set LSP client options for rustaceanvim's LSP client using `vim.lsp.config`.\nBecause it enables picking up configs that were set for multiple clients (e.g. with a `\"*\"` key), I decided that it would be useful and added it.\n\n**But rustaceanvim only merges it with the `server` (`rustaceanvim.lsp.ClientOpts`) field, not the general plugin configuration**\n\n> Especially with the default_settings. It is redundant as it is the same as settings. Not sure why one would set default_settings via vim.lsp.config if you can set settings directly instead.\n>\n> Maybe @mrcjkb could clarify.\n\nThis is slightly off-topic, but here's the clarification:\n\nIn `rustaceanvim.lsp.ClientOpts`, `settings` is of type `table | fun(project_root:string|nil, default_settings: table):table`.\nThe default implementation (`@type fun(project_root:string|nil, default_settings: table):table`) uses heuristics to set certain defaults based on the runtime environment (e.g. enabling Clippy diagnostics if Clippy is available).\n`default_settings` exists so that you can statically configure default LSP client options using a table, without losing the dynamic configuration at runtime. If you don't want the dynamic runtime configuration, you can configure `settings` as a `table` instead of using `default_settings`.\n\nIn short, `vim.lsp.ClientConfig` fields are _compatible_ with `rustaceanvim.lsp.ClientOpts` but _the reverse is not true_.\nSo yes, the fact that it is possible to set arbitrary fields that are specific to rustaceanvim's implementation is an accident.\n",
